How the Solution Answers the Hammerhead Case Study
The codebase is organized as a Python package (novacool/) with six modules and five runner scripts. Each module handles a distinct concern, and each script addresses one or more of the five tasks. Let me walk through everything.

Architecture Overview
The package is split into these files, each with a clear role:

config.py — all physical constants and facility parameters in a single dataclass. thermal.py — the lumped-parameter thermal solver. power.py — the electrical power path (UPS, fans, pumps, chiller, PUE). data.py — CSV loading utilities. simulator.py — couples thermal + power into a step-by-step simulator. controllers.py — three control policies (baseline, heuristic, PID). env.py — the Gym-style RL environment wrapper.

Task 1 — Thermal Model (thermal.py)
This is the physics core of the whole project. The model uses a lumped-parameter (reduced-order) approach — instead of doing full CFD, it treats each CRAH zone as one thermal "lump" and tracks a handful of temperatures per zone. Here are the key equations:

Rack energy balance (heat absorbed by air passing through a rack):

The temperature rise across a single rack is derived from the first law of thermodynamics for steady airflow:

ΔT_rack = P_rack / (ṁ_rack × c_p)

where P_rack is the rack's electrical power draw in watts (since all IT power becomes heat), ṁ_rack is the mass flow rate of air through that rack in kg/s, and c_p is the specific heat of air (1005 J/kg·K). The outlet temperature of each rack is then simply T_inlet + ΔT_rack. This is a direct application of Q = ṁ·c_p·ΔT, the fundamental convective heat transfer equation.

Airflow distribution within a zone: Total airflow per zone is ṁ_CRAH = ṁ_nominal × fan_speed. Within a zone, air is distributed proportionally to each rack's power draw (hotter racks draw more air, mimicking back-pressure effects), with a floor of 25% of the uniform share to prevent starvation of idle racks.

CRAH return temperature (zone-level energy balance):

T_return = T_cold_aisle + (Q_zone × 1000) / (ṁ_zone × c_p)

This is the same energy-balance equation but applied to the entire zone: all the IT heat from racks in that zone raises the air temperature from cold-aisle to hot-aisle return.

CRAH cooling: The CRAH cools the return air back down to the supply setpoint, with a floor of T_chilled_water + 3°C (you can't cool air below the chilled-water temperature plus a realistic approach delta). The heat removed is:

Q_cooling = ṁ_zone × c_p × (T_return − T_supply_actual) / 1000 [kW]

Cold-aisle dynamics (first-order thermal lag): The cold aisle has thermal mass — it doesn't instantly reach the supply temperature. This is modeled as a first-order exponential lag:

T_cold_new = (1 − α) × T_cold_old + α × T_target

where α = Δt / (τ + Δt) and τ is the time constant (2 minutes by default, converted to seconds). T_target blends the CRAH supply air with a small hot-aisle bypass (3% by default, modeling imperfect containment):

T_target = (1 − bypass_frac) × T_supply + bypass_frac × T_return

This first-order lag is a standard method for representing thermal inertia in lumped-parameter models.

run_sim.py drives this: it loads the workload CSV, runs 1440 one-minute steps under the no-control baseline (fixed CRAH setpoints), and produces the four required plots — cold-aisle temperature, hot-aisle temperature, peak outlet temperature, and cooling power over 24 hours.

Task 2 — Power & System Coupling (power.py)
This module models every component of the electrical power path:

UPS efficiency (quadratic curve):

η(x) = η_peak − k × (x − x_peak)²

With defaults η_peak = 0.965 (96.5% peak efficiency), x_peak = 0.65 (peak at 65% load), and k = 0.20. This means the UPS is most efficient at around 50–75% load and wastes more power at very low or very high loads. The UPS input power is then P_IT / η. Since the facility uses 2N redundancy, each UPS module sees half the total IT load.

Fan power (affinity laws):

P_fan = P_nominal × speed³

This is the classic fan affinity law — aerodynamic power scales with the cube of rotational speed. This makes fan speed a very powerful control lever: halving the speed reduces fan power by 87.5%.

Pump power: Scales linearly with cooling duty (fraction of zone capacity being used), with a 15% idle floor representing minimum circulation.

Chiller power: Computed via a Coefficient of Performance (COP) model:

P_chiller = Q_total_cooling / COP

The COP degrades in two ways: colder supply setpoints (every degree below 18°C costs 0.08 COP), and higher ambient temperatures (every degree above 25°C costs 0.05 COP), floored at COP = 2.0. This captures the real thermodynamic reality that producing colder air costs more energy, and rejecting heat to a hotter outdoors is harder.

PUE:

PUE = (P_UPS_input + P_fans + P_pumps + P_chiller + P_other) / P_IT

A small "other" overhead (1% of capacity) covers lights, security, and networking.

The run_sim.py script plots PUE over the 24-hour period alongside the ambient temperature curve, showing how PUE worsens when ambient temperature peaks in the afternoon and when IT load drops (since fixed overheads become a larger fraction).

Task 3 — Validation & Calibration (run_validation.py + run_calibration.py)
Validation runs the simulator under the same baseline conditions and compares simulated inlet/outlet temperatures against the reference sensor CSV. It computes RMSE, MAE, max absolute error, and bias. The initial results with the default 18°C supply setpoint show a large bias (~+10°C inlet, +14°C outlet) — the model is running much warmer than the reference data, suggesting the real facility operates with colder supply air.

Calibration (run_calibration.py) does a grid search over supply-temperature setpoints (7.5–12°C in 0.5°C steps) and fan speeds (0.6–1.0 in 0.1 steps). The best fit is found at 8.5°C supply / 100% fan speed. After calibration, errors drop dramatically: inlet RMSE from 9.8°C down to 1.7°C, outlet RMSE from 15.1°C down to 4.4°C. The worst divergence still occurs around hour 13.7 (early afternoon), likely because the simple sinusoidal ambient model doesn't capture real weather patterns and the lumped model misses transient effects during peak load transitions.

Task 4 — Control Policies (controllers.py + run_control.py)
Three policies are implemented and compared:

NoControlBaseline — holds CRAH supply at a fixed 18°C with 80% fan speed. This deliberately creates a control problem: the facility hits 52.5°C peak outlet with 796 minutes of thermal violations.

HeuristicController — a zone-aware proportional controller. For each zone, it measures the peak rack outlet temperature and computes an error relative to a target (34°C). It then adjusts supply setpoint down and fan speed up proportionally to that error. If any rack gets within 4°C of the 40°C hard limit, it switches to emergency mode (coldest supply, maximum fan). Result: only 9 minutes of violations, peak 40.7°C.

PIDController — a full proportional-integral-derivative controller on the same per-zone peak temperature. The integral term handles steady-state offsets, and the derivative term dampens oscillations. It also has a hard safety override at 37°C. Result: zero violations, peak 39.6°C.

Both controllers achieve the same IT throughput (108.94 MWh — the workload is fixed, not curtailed), but spend slightly more on cooling (~31 MWh vs. 28 MWh for baseline) because they push the supply temperature colder when needed. PUE goes from 1.339 (baseline) to ~1.36, which is slightly higher on average because the controllers use more cooling power — but the baseline's low PUE is misleading since it's letting the facility overheat.

Task 5 — RL Environment (env.py + run_env_demo.py)
The DataCenterEnv class wraps the simulator with a Gym-compatible reset()/step() interface.

Observation space (20-dimensional float vector): per-zone cold-aisle temperature, return temperature, peak outlet temperature, and zone power (4 zones × 4 = 16), plus total IT load, ambient temperature, and sin/cos encoding of time-of-day (cyclic so midnight doesn't have a discontinuity).

Action space (8-dimensional): 4 CRAH supply setpoints (12–24°C) and 4 fan speed fractions (0.1–1.0).

Reward function:

r_t = w_it × IT_load_MW − w_pen × Σ max(0, T_peak − 40)² − w_eng × P_total_MW − w_hot × max(0, T_hot_mean − 38)

The weights are: throughput (1.0), safety penalty (5.0, squared to heavily punish violations), energy cost (0.15, small enough to be a tiebreaker), and a soft hot-aisle cap (0.5). The squared penalty term is crucial — it makes small violations cheap to explore but large violations extremely expensive, guiding the agent to stay well below the limit.

Episode termination: either the 24-hour window ends, or a critical violation occurs (any rack > 45°C), representing an unrecoverable thermal runaway.

The run_env_demo.py script exercises this by running both a random policy and the heuristic through the environment, plotting cumulative reward to show the environment differentiates good from bad behavior.

Summary of Physics Equations
All the physics boil down to a few fundamental principles:

Conservation of energy (first law of thermodynamics): Q = ṁ·c_p·ΔT — heat added to air equals mass flow × heat capacity × temperature rise
First-order thermal dynamics: dT/dt = (T_target − T) / τ — discretized as an exponential moving average
Fan affinity laws: P ∝ speed³ — from fluid mechanics similarity laws
Chiller thermodynamics: COP degrades with colder setpoints and hotter ambient (Carnot-like behavior)
UPS efficiency: quadratic curve peaking at partial load — standard for double-conversion UPS systems
The modular separation means any of these sub-models can be swapped independently — for example, replacing the sinusoidal ambient model with real weather data, or adding a humidity module alongside the thermal solver.

why do we have ΔT_rack = P_rack / (ṁ_rack × c_p)? doesn't it suppose P_rack is entirely converted to heat?

Yes, exactly — and that assumption is intentional and physically well-justified for a data center.

In a server rack, essentially all of the electrical power drawn by the IT equipment ends up as heat. A CPU or GPU converts electrical energy into computation, but the computation itself doesn't store energy — it dissipates as thermal energy through resistive losses in transistors. Memory, storage drives, power supplies, network switches — same story. The only energy that leaves the rack without becoming local heat is the tiny amount carried away by network cables as electromagnetic signals, which is negligible (microwatts vs. kilowatts).

So the equation comes from a straightforward energy balance on a control volume around the rack. Air enters at temperature T_inlet, absorbs all the dissipated heat Q, and leaves at T_outlet. Conservation of energy gives:

Q = ṁ × c_p × (T_outlet − T_inlet)

Rearranging for the temperature rise: ΔT = Q / (ṁ × c_p). And since Q = P_rack (all electrical power becomes heat), you get the equation in the code.

This is a standard assumption in data center thermal engineering. ASHRAE's thermal guidelines for data centers use it, and real facility operators measure cooling load directly from IT electrical metering for exactly this reason. The only scenario where it breaks down slightly is if a facility has significant hot-water liquid cooling that removes heat through a separate path before the air picks it up — but in this model the facility uses traditional air cooling via CRAHs, so the assumption holds cleanly.

The more subtle approximation in that equation is actually the steady-state part — it assumes the air passing through the rack reaches thermal equilibrium instantaneously, with no transient heat storage in the rack's metal chassis. That's reasonable at the one-minute timestep this simulator uses, since the air transit time through a rack is on the order of seconds.

