Thought process
Thought process
Partially, but not fully as the case study prompt describes.

What IS modeled:

The chilled-water supply temperature is configurable — chw_supply_temp_c: 7.0 in config.py. It's used as a physical floor on how cold the CRAH can make the supply air (supply_actual = max(setpoints[z], cfg.chw_supply_temp_c + 3.0)), which represents the minimum approach temperature between chilled water and supply air across the coil.

The heat removal itself is modeled through an air-side energy balance:

Q_cooling = ṁ_air × c_p × (T_return − T_supply)

This correctly captures how much heat the CRAH pulls out of the return air.

Chilled-water pump power is also modeled in power.py, scaling with cooling duty plus a 15% idle floor.

What is NOT explicitly modeled:

The chilled-water flow rate is not a first-class variable. There's no m_dot_chw state, no CW valve position, no CW return temperature. The model assumes the CW valve has "enough authority" to deliver whatever cooling is commanded, as long as the setpoint is above the CHW_supply + 3°C floor. The pump power scales with cooling duty as a proxy, but you can't independently set the CW flow rate as a control input.

A more faithful implementation of the spec would add:

A CW mass flow rate ṁ_chw as either a state or control variable
A heat exchanger effectiveness model: Q = ε × ṁ_min × c_p × (T_return_air − T_chw_supply), where ε depends on both flow rates (NTU-effectiveness method)
A CW return temperature from energy balance: T_chw_return = T_chw_supply + Q / (ṁ_chw × c_p_water)
CW flow as an actuator alongside fan speed
Why the simplification is defensible:

For the control and RL problems in Tasks 4 and 5, the two actuators that actually matter from an operator's perspective are fan speed and supply-air setpoint — those are what a real BMS operator tunes. The CW loop is usually managed by a lower-level loop that tracks the commanded supply-air temperature. So collapsing the CW dynamics into "the valve hits the setpoint unless physically impossible" is a reasonable reduced-order choice, but it does mean the simulator can't answer questions like "what if we raise CHW supply from 7°C to 10°C to save chiller energy?" without modifying the model — those questions would require the full heat-exchanger treatment.

