how long does it take the rack (50kW) of a data center to heat up without cooling


Thought process
Thought process
Short answer: seconds for the air, a couple of minutes for the bulk of the rack, and servers will typically throttle or shut down long before anything external reaches 40 °C.

Here's the physics.

The heat equation for an adiabatic (no heat leaves) rack is just:

dT/dt = P / (m · c_p)

So the answer depends entirely on which thermal mass you're asking about.

Just the air trapped inside the rack (instantaneous response). A 42U rack is roughly 1.2 m³ of interior volume, which holds about 1.5 kg of air. With c_p = 1005 J/(kg·K):

dT/dt = 50,000 W / (1.5 kg × 1005 J/kg·K) ≈ 33 K per second

A 20 °C → 40 °C rise takes under one second if no air moves through. This is why any cooling loss alarms immediately — even seconds without airflow push inlet temperatures out of spec.

The whole rack as a thermal lump (air + chassis metal + server bodies). A fully populated 42U rack weighs roughly 600–800 kg, a mix of steel, aluminum, PCBs, and silicon with an effective c_p ≈ 500 J/(kg·K). That gives a thermal capacity of roughly 350,000 J/K, so:

dT/dt = 50,000 / 350,000 ≈ 0.14 K per second ≈ 8.6 K per minute

Starting from 20 °C, the bulk temperature reaches 40 °C after about 2 to 2.5 minutes, and it would continue climbing toward steady-state if there were no heat loss to the room.

What actually happens first, though, is internal silicon overheating. CPU/GPU dies have tiny thermal mass (~0.01 J/K per die) and dissipate several hundred watts each. In a no-airflow condition, junction temperatures rise at tens of K/s and hit the thermal-throttle threshold (around 85–95 °C) within 10–30 seconds. ASHRAE tier-1 equipment is designed to auto-shut-down before 45 °C inlet, and modern servers protect themselves at the silicon level much earlier.

In practice, data center thermal safety cases are written around a "two-minute ride-through" for the air-handling side — that matches the bulk-rack number above and is why UPS systems must carry not only the IT load but also the CRAH fans through any power interruption.

but if we consider the rack should n't we also have an equation P = m* Cp * DT with the thermal capacity of the rack?

Yes — that's exactly the right framing, and it's what gives you the ~2-minute number I quoted for the bulk rack. Let me make it explicit.

The integrated form of the energy balance
Starting from the adiabatic energy equation:

P · dt = m · c_p · dT

which is just Q = m · c_p · ΔT written in differential form. If P is constant and there's no cooling, integrating from time 0 to t gives:

P · t = m · c_p · ΔT

or rearranged for the time to reach a given temperature rise:

t = (m · c_p · ΔT) / P

Applied to a 50 kW rack
With a bulk thermal capacity of roughly m · c_p ≈ 350,000 J/K (mixed steel/aluminum/PCB/silicon, ~700 kg at effective c_p ≈ 500 J/kg·K) and a target rise of ΔT = 20 K (from 20 °C inlet to 40 °C):

t = (350,000 J/K × 20 K) / 50,000 W = 140 seconds ≈ 2.3 minutes

That matches the dT/dt ≈ 0.14 K/s rate I gave earlier — it's the same equation, just integrated.

Why the air-only and bulk-rack answers are both valid
You actually have two thermal masses in play, coupled:

m_air · c_p,air · dT_air/dt = P − h·A · (T_air − T_metal)

m_metal · c_p,metal · dT_metal/dt = h·A · (T_air − T_metal)

In the very short term (seconds), all the heat dumps into the air because the metal hasn't had time to respond — that's where the 33 K/s number comes from. Over minutes, heat equilibrates into the chassis and servers, and the effective thermal mass becomes the full rack — that's the 0.14 K/s regime.

A slightly better lumped model
If you wanted one equation covering both regimes, you'd use the total thermal capacity of the rack + its contents as your lumped m·c_p, which gives the 140-second answer. That's the standard engineering approach: treat the rack as a single thermal mass and write:

(m · c_p)_rack · dT/dt = P_IT − Q_cooling

With Q_cooling = 0 and initial T = 20 °C:

T(t) = T₀ + P · t / (m · c_p)

a linear ramp until cooling kicks in. This is literally the integrated form of the equation you just suggested, and it's exactly the right tool for "ride-through" calculations — how long can a data center lose cooling before things go bad.

Realistic thermal-mass numbers for a modern 50 kW rack
Component	Mass (kg)	c_p (J/kg·K)	Capacity (J/K)
Chassis steel	~100	490	49,000
Server aluminum heatsinks	~50	900	45,000
PCBs, cables, connectors	~80	1,200	96,000
Silicon, memory, storage	~40	700	28,000
Internal air	~1.5	1,005	1,500
Power supplies, transformers	~30	500	15,000
Total	~300	—	~235,000
So a more defensible number is m · c_p ≈ 200,000 – 350,000 J/K for a 50 kW rack, giving a ride-through of ~80 – 140 seconds before ΔT = 20 K. Either way, you end up in the "roughly two minutes" range, which is why the industry-standard UPS ride-through for CRAH fans is typically specified as at least 90 seconds to 2 minutes.

