rack_m_dot[mask] = m_dot_crah[z] * np.clip(share, 0.25 / self._racks_per_zone, None)
So a rack drawing 40 kW gets roughly 4× the airflow of a rack drawing 10 kW in the same zone (with a 25%-of-uniform floor so idle racks don't get starved). Because rack power varies over the 24-hour workload, the per-rack airflow varies too — even if fan speed stays constant, rack_m_dot changes every minute as the workload changes.

What IS constant
cfg.crah_nominal_airflow_kgs = 65.0 — the nominal design-point airflow per CRAH at 100% speed
CP_AIR = 1005.0 J/(kg·K) — air specific heat
RHO_AIR = 1.2 kg/m³ — air density (not actually used in the thermal calc; it's just a constant)
The geometric mapping from rack to zone (rack_to_crah)
Physically, is proportional-to-power airflow realistic?
It's a rough surrogate for rack-internal fans + back-pressure effects: in a real facility, hotter racks pull more CRAH supply air because their server fans spin faster, creating more draft. But it is an approximation — real airflow distribution is set by the pressure field in the cold-aisle plenum and the aerodynamic resistance of each rack, which would need a CFD or network-flow solver to capture accurately. The code's proportional-share model is a simple stand-in that behaves correctly in the two limiting cases (uniform load → uniform flow; highly skewed load → skewed flow) and keeps the zone total mass flow exactly equal to ṁ_zone.

So ṁ_air is a dynamic quantity driven by (a) controller actions on fan speed and (b) the workload's spatial distribution across racks.

where does 65 comes from?

The 65 kg/s comes from a reverse-engineered design calculation — the author picked it so the model would produce a realistic hot-aisle temperature rise at nominal load. There's a comment in config.py that basically admits this:

python
# CRAH nominal airflow per unit at 100 % fan speed (kg/s).
# Chosen to give ~15-20 K rise across racks at nominal load.
crah_nominal_airflow_kgs: float = 65.0
Where that number comes from physically
Work backwards from the target ΔT across a zone using the same Q = ṁ·c_p·ΔT equation we've been using:

Nominal IT load per zone at design point: 10 MW / 4 zones × ~80% utilization ≈ 2 MW ≈ 2,000 kW
Target hot-aisle rise: ΔT ≈ 15 K (industry-standard cold-aisle/hot-aisle split)
Air specific heat: c_p = 1005 J/(kg·K)
Solving for ṁ: ṁ = Q / (c_p · ΔT) = 2,000,000 W / (1005 J/kg·K × 15 K) ≈ 132 kg/s
That gives ~130 kg/s at peak zone load. The 65 kg/s nominal in the config is roughly half of that, which makes sense because:

The workload average is well below the 2 MW peak — closer to 1 MW per zone during the 24-hour trace (the whole facility averages ~4.5 MW IT, not 10 MW)
Plugging 1 MW into the same formula: ṁ = 1,000,000 / (1005 × 15) ≈ 66 kg/s ✓
So 65 kg/s is the airflow that makes the facility hit ~15 K rise at average workload, not peak. At peak load with only 65 kg/s, the rise would be twice as large (~30 K), which is exactly why the baseline simulation goes thermally unstable — the CRAHs are physically undersized for the peak.

Sanity check against real CRAH units
Real data center CRAH/CRAC units are typically rated in CFM (cubic feet per minute) or m³/h. Converting 65 kg/s to volumetric flow at 20 °C:

Air density ≈ 1.2 kg/m³
Volumetric flow = 65 / 1.2 ≈ 54 m³/s ≈ 115,000 CFM
A large modern CRAH unit is typically rated at 25,000–40,000 CFM, so 115,000 CFM would represent about 3–4 large CRAH modules per zone, or equivalently a single very large downflow unit with multiple EC fans. That's plausible for a 10 MW facility where each of the 4 zones handles 2.5 MW — you'd expect multiple CRAH fan arrays per zone.

Is it physically rigorous?
Not really — it's a design-level sizing number, not a measured or first-principles value. A more defensible approach would be to:

Specify the CRAH make/model and pull its fan curve from the datasheet
Compute volumetric flow as a function of fan speed and pressure rise
Couple that to a plenum pressure model
But for a case-study digital twin, picking a ṁ_nominal that produces the right ΔT at average load is a standard shortcut, and the comment in the code is honest about it being chosen rather than derived.

is ṁ_zone = sum(ṁ_rack) ?

Yes — the code explicitly enforces this invariant by renormalizing. Let me show you the exact mechanism in rack_mass_flow():

python
# First pass: proportional share with a floor
for z in range(cfg.n_crahs):
    mask = self._rack_zone == z
    p_zone = rack_power_kw[mask]
    share = p_zone / max(p_zone.sum(), 1e-6)
    rack_m_dot[mask] = m_dot_crah[z] * np.clip(share, 0.25 / self._racks_per_zone, None)

# Second pass: renormalise so the zone total exactly equals m_dot_crah[z]
for z in range(cfg.n_crahs):
    mask = self._rack_zone == z
    s = rack_m_dot[mask].sum()
    if s > 0:
        rack_m_dot[mask] *= m_dot_crah[z] / s
Why two passes?
The first pass distributes airflow proportionally to rack power, with a floor (0.25 / racks_per_zone) so idle racks still get some minimum air. That floor breaks the proportionality — after the first pass, the shares no longer sum to 1 exactly, so the rack total doesn't equal the zone total.

The second pass fixes that by scaling every rack's flow by the ratio m_dot_crah[z] / s, where s is the current sum. After this scaling:

Σ ṁ_rack_i (over all racks in zone z) = ṁ_zone[z]

exactly, by construction. It's a projection back onto the "total airflow = CRAH airflow" constraint.

Why this matters for the energy balance
This invariant is what makes the two forms of the zone energy balance equivalent:

Per-rack form:

P_i = ṁ_rack_i · c_p · (T_out_i − T_in)

Zone-level form:

Q_zone = ṁ_zone · c_p · (T_return − T_cold)

Summing the per-rack form over all racks in a zone:

Σ P_i = c_p · Σ ṁ_rack_i · (T_out_i − T_in)

Q_zone = c_p · (Σ ṁ_rack_i · T_out_i − T_in · Σ ṁ_rack_i)

The mass-flow-weighted mean outlet temperature is the definition of T_return:

T_return ≡ (Σ ṁ_rack_i · T_out_i) / (Σ ṁ_rack_i)

And the renormalization guarantees Σ ṁ_rack_i = ṁ_zone, so:

Q_zone = c_p · ṁ_zone · (T_return − T_cold) ✓

Without the second pass, there would be a mass-conservation mismatch: the code would claim to deliver 65 kg/s at the CRAH but actually distribute something slightly more than that to the racks (because of the floor), and the two energy balances would disagree by a small amount. The renormalization is mass conservation enforced as an explicit step.

Subtle note
Mass is conserved per zone but not redistributed across zones — airflow cannot leak between zones in this model. That's a simplification: in a real facility with shared cold-aisle plenums, hot zones can "steal" air from cold zones via pressure gradients. The lumped model ignores that cross-zone coupling.

How is T_out_i determined?

T_out_i is determined directly from the per-rack steady-state energy balance. Here's the exact chain of steps in thermal.py:

The calculation
python
rack_m_dot = self.rack_mass_flow(rack_power_kw, fan_speeds)           # (1) per-rack airflow
rack_inlet = np.array(
    [state.zones[self._rack_zone[r]].cold_aisle_temp_c for r in range(cfg.n_racks)]
)                                                                      # (2) per-rack inlet
rack_delta_t = (rack_power_kw * 1000.0) / np.maximum(rack_m_dot * CP_AIR, 1.0)  # (3) ΔT
rack_outlet = rack_inlet + rack_delta_t                                # (4) T_out_i
Step by step
Step 1 — Per-rack mass flow ṁ_i. Computed by rack_mass_flow() as discussed in the previous messages: the zone total ṁ_zone = 65 × fan_speed kg/s is distributed to racks proportionally to their power, with a floor for idle racks, then renormalized so Σ ṁ_i = ṁ_zone.

Step 2 — Per-rack inlet temperature T_in_i. Every rack in a given zone sees the same inlet temperature, equal to that zone's current cold-aisle temperature:

T_in_i = T_cold_aisle[zone(i)]

This is a simplification — it assumes the cold aisle is perfectly mixed within a zone, so all 50 racks in zone 0 see identical inlet air. It ignores spatial gradients along the aisle (which in reality can be 2–5 K from one end to the other).

Step 3 — Temperature rise across the rack ΔT_i. This is the steady-state energy balance from the first law of thermodynamics:

ΔT_i = P_i · 1000 / (ṁ_i · c_p)

The factor of 1000 converts kW to W. The np.maximum(..., 1.0) is just a numerical guard against division-by-zero for degenerate cases.

Step 4 — Outlet temperature T_out_i.

T_out_i = T_in_i + ΔT_i

That's it. There's no lag, no thermal mass, no iteration — it's a one-line algebraic formula.

What this means physically
Substituting everything back:

T_out_i = T_cold_aisle[zone(i)] + P_i · 1000 / (ṁ_i · c_p)

So T_out_i depends on three things:

The cold-aisle temperature of its zone (which evolves slowly via the first-order lag on T_cold)
The rack's own power draw from the workload CSV
The airflow it receives, which in turn depends on fan speed and the proportional-share distribution
Why this is "per-rack" and not uniform
Even though every rack in a zone sees the same inlet, they get different outlets because:

P_i varies rack-to-rack (from the workload trace)
ṁ_i varies rack-to-rack (proportional to power, with the floor)
Interestingly, because ṁ_i ∝ P_i in the proportional-share scheme, the ratio P_i / ṁ_i is roughly constant across racks in a zone — so in the pure-proportional limit, all racks in a zone would reach approximately the same outlet temperature. The floor 0.25 / racks_per_zone breaks this: low-power racks get a disproportionate share of air and run cooler than average, while high-power racks that lose air to the floor run hotter than average. That's how the simulator gets a non-trivial distribution of rack_outlet_temp_c values, which the controllers then use to detect the "hottest rack" for safety.

Feedback through the zone
After all per-rack T_out_i values are computed, they're used by:

The safety check rack_outlet_temp_c.max() > 40°C (controllers watch the hottest rack)
Nothing else directly — the zone return temperature is computed independently from the zone-level balance T_return = T_cold + Q_zone / (ṁ_zone · c_p), which, as we showed earlier, equals the mass-flow-weighted mean of the individual T_out_i values because Σ ṁ_i = ṁ_zone.
So the per-rack outlets are mostly used for observability and safety, while the zone-level return is what actually drives the CRAH cooling calculation and the cold-aisle lag update.

For the chilled water loop with fixed efficiency, what is C_min, is it C_air or C_chw?

It depends on the operating point — C_min is whichever of C_air or C_chw is smaller at that moment, and which one wins is not a fixed answer. Let me work through the numbers.

The two heat capacity rates
C_air = ṁ_air · c_p,air = ṁ_air × 1005 J/(kg·K)

C_chw = ṁ_chw · c_p,water = ṁ_chw × 4186 J/(kg·K)

Water's specific heat is about 4.16× larger than air's. So for the two to be equal, you'd need:

ṁ_chw / ṁ_air = 1005 / 4186 ≈ 0.24

In words: C_air = C_chw when the water flow rate is about a quarter of the air flow rate (by mass). When the water flow is lower than 24% of the air flow, the water is the limiting side; when it's higher, the air is the limiting side.

Plugging in the values from our models
In thermal_fixed_eps.py the nominal flows are:

crah_nominal_airflow_kgs = 65.0 kg/s (from config.py)
chw_nominal_kgs = 40.0 kg/s (from FixedEpsCoilConfig)
At nominal operation (fan 85%, CW flow 80%):

ṁ_air = 65 × 0.85 = 55.25 kg/s → C_air = 55.25 × 1005 ≈ 55,500 W/K
ṁ_chw = 40 × 0.80 = 32 kg/s → C_chw = 32 × 4186 ≈ 134,000 W/K
So at the nominal design point, C_air < C_chw, and therefore C_min = C_air ≈ 55,500 W/K. The air side is the limiting side.

Why this makes physical sense
Because C_air is smaller, the air temperature changes more than the water temperature for a given Q. In our model at nominal load, a zone needs to remove roughly 2,000 kW of heat. The temperature changes on each side are:

ΔT_air = Q / C_air = 2,000,000 / 55,500 ≈ 36 K (the air cools by 36 K across the coil)
ΔT_chw = Q / C_chw = 2,000,000 / 134,000 ≈ 15 K (the water warms by 15 K)
That's the standard "large air ΔT, small water ΔT" signature of a CRAH coil, and it's what you'd expect physically: you're trying to produce a large temperature swing on the air side (from ~30 °C return down to ~12 °C supply) and the water loop is sized to carry the heat away with a modest supply-return split (7 °C in, ~22 °C out).

When would C_chw become C_min?
Only in unusual operating modes:

Very low CW flow. If the pump runs at the minimum idle fraction (10% × 40 = 4 kg/s), then C_chw = 4 × 4186 ≈ 17,000 W/K, which is well below C_air. In that regime the water becomes the bottleneck — it saturates at its maximum temperature rise long before the air does.
Very high fan speed with low pump. Same effect — ṁ_air goes up, ṁ_chw stays down, and the crossover happens around ṁ_chw ≈ 0.24 × ṁ_air.
A facility designed for larger water-side ΔT. Some data centers use a smaller CW flow with higher supply-return split (say 7 °C → 27 °C, 20 K rise) to reduce pumping energy. In that topology C_chw would be smaller and the water side would routinely be the limiting resistance.
Consequence for the effectiveness equation
The formula Q = ε · C_min · (T_return_air − T_chw_supply) uses C_min because it's a physical upper bound: whichever stream has the smaller capacity rate hits the other stream's inlet temperature first (ε = 1 is the ideal limit). With C_min = C_air, the maximum possible cooling is:

Q_max = C_air · (T_return − T_chw_supply)

At T_return = 30 °C, T_chw_supply = 7 °C, that's Q_max = 55,500 × 23 ≈ 1,275 kW per zone at ε = 1. With the realistic ε = 0.7, we get ~890 kW per zone — which, multiplied by 4 zones, is 3.6 MW of cooling capacity at the nominal design point. That's lower than the peak IT load, which is why the comparison script will show the fixed-eps model struggling at full workload unless both fan speed and CW flow are pushed toward maximum.

In short
At nominal operation in the fixed-eps model, C_min = C_air (air is the limiting side), because c_p,water is 4× c_p,air and the design mass flow ratio (ṁ_chw/ṁ_air ≈ 0.6) doesn't offset that factor. You only get C_min = C_chw if the pump drops below ~24% of the air mass flow.

the air cools by 36 K across the coil, why?


Thought process
Thought process
Good catch — I actually overstated that number in the previous message. Let me correct it, because the math leads to a cleaner and more illuminating answer.

The mistake I made
In the previous message I wrote "ΔT_air = Q / C_air = 2,000,000 / 55,500 ≈ 36 K" by plugging in the zone IT load (2 MW) as the cooling duty. But that's not what Q actually is in the fixed-ε model — it's what the zone needs, not what the coil can deliver. You can't just assume the coil removes whatever heat you want; Q is constrained by the effectiveness equation.

The correct calculation
The fixed-ε model says:

Q = ε · C_min · (T_return_air − T_chw_supply)

At nominal conditions (ε = 0.70, C_min = C_air ≈ 55,500 W/K, T_return = 30 °C, T_chw_supply = 7 °C, driving ΔT = 23 K):

Q = 0.70 × 55,500 × 23 ≈ 894 kW

Then the air temperature change across the coil comes from the air-side balance Q = C_air · ΔT_air:

ΔT_air = Q / C_air = 894,000 / 55,500 ≈ 16 K

So the air actually cools by 16 K, not 36 K. The coil takes the return air from 30 °C down to roughly 14 °C — which is a realistic CRAH supply temperature.

Why this specific number — the elegant form
When C_min = C_air (the air is the limiting side), the air temperature drop simplifies dramatically. Starting from the effectiveness definition:

ΔT_air = Q / C_air = (ε · C_min · driving) / C_air

and since C_min = C_air, the C_air cancels:

ΔT_air = ε · (T_return_air − T_chw_supply)

That's the physical meaning of effectiveness on the air-limited side: ε is literally the fraction of the maximum possible temperature drop that the air actually achieves. With ε = 0.70 and a 23 K driving gap, you get 70% × 23 = 16.1 K. An ideal coil (ε = 1) would drop the air all the way down to T_chw_supply = 7 °C; a real coil only gets 70% of the way there.

On the water side, since C_chw > C_air, the water temperature only rises by a smaller amount:

ΔT_chw = Q / C_chw = 894,000 / 134,000 ≈ 6.7 K

So the water goes from 7 °C supply to ~13.7 °C return, and the air goes from 30 °C return to ~14 °C supply. The water-side rise is smaller than the air-side drop by exactly the capacity-rate ratio, C_air / C_chw ≈ 0.41.

The sanity check that catches the error
A useful check: for any counterflow or crossflow HX, the ratio of the two ΔTs must equal the inverse ratio of C values:

ΔT_air / ΔT_chw = C_chw / C_air

16 K / 6.7 K ≈ 2.4, which equals 134,000 / 55,500 ≈ 2.4 ✓. My earlier "36 K air / 15 K water" numbers had the same ratio (~2.4) because I computed both from the same Q, but they violated the effectiveness ceiling — the coil isn't capable of delivering 2 MW at ε = 0.7 and that driving temperature.

The consequence
This is actually the point of the fixed-ε model: it exposes the cooling capacity limit that the baseline "perfect tracker" model hid. In the baseline code, the CRAH just magically delivers whatever supply temperature you ask for (down to T_chw + 3 K). In the fixed-ε model, with these parameters, the coil tops out at ~900 kW per zone ≈ 3.6 MW facility-wide, which is less than the peak workload. The simulator would have to either run fans harder (raising C_air), open CW valves wider (raising C_chw, though it's not the limiting side here), or accept that supply air cannot go below 14 °C — all of which are physically realistic tradeoffs the baseline model skips over.

So the short answer to your question: the air doesn't cool by 36 K — it cools by about 16 K, which is ε × (T_return − T_chw_supply). I was sloppy in the previous message and computed Q the wrong way. Good that you pushed back on it.